Because the destroy plan only creates the necessary changes for apply to
remove all the resources, it does no reading of resources or data
sources, leading to stale data in the state. In most cases this is not a
problem, but when a provider configuration is using resource values, the
provider may not be able to run correctly during apply. In prior
versions of terraform, the implicit refresh that happened during
`terraform destroy` would update the data sources and remove missing
resources from state as required.

The destroy plan graph has a minimal amount of information, so it is not
feasible to work the reading of resources into the operation without
completely replicating the normal plan graph, and updating the plan
graph and all destroy node implementation is also a considerable amount
of refactoring. Instead, we can run a normal plan which is used to
refresh the state before creating the destroy plan. This brings back
similar behavior to core versions prior to 0.14, and the refresh can
still be skipped using the `-refresh=false` cli flag.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/bmelbourne/terraform/commits/0b3b84acc1ade2e394fcb7e3b956bf2ea0789eb1"},{"sha":"e614fb9aed597252e6ca18244ca779e0d61d3683","author":{"name":"James Bardin","email":"62973226c85cb5a1996aaed2ce372ac02dcad8b7@gmail.com"},"message":"refresh is expected for destroy

[{"sha":"e865faf318950f4b86b15d2e56c4c3ec0667709a","author":{"name":"Martin Atkins","email":"a1bdfbfb01322b54f9edf8cea8f328c9384b211a@degeneration.co.uk"},"message":"command: Better visual hierarchy for diagnostics

I frequently see people attempting to ask questions about Terraform's
error and warning messages but either only copying part of the message or
accidentally copying a surrounding paragraph that isn't part of the
message.

While I'm sure some of these are just "careless" mistakes, I've also
noticed that this has sometimes overlapped with someone asking a question
whose answer is written directly in the part of the message they didn't
include when copying, and so I have a theory that our current output
doesn't create a good enough visual hierarchy for sighted users to
understand where the diagnostic messages start and end when we show them
in close proximity to other content, or to other diagnostic messages.
As a result, some folks fail to notice the relevant message that might've
answered their question.

I tried a few different experiments for different approaches here, such
as adding more horizontal rules to the output and coloring the detail
text differently, but the approach that felt like the nicest compromise
to me was what's implemented here, which is to add a vertical line
along the left edge of each diagnostic message, colored to match with the
typical color we use for each diagnostic severity. This means that the
diagnostics end up slightly indented from what's around them, and the
vertical line seems to help subtly signal how we intended the content
to be grouped together.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/hashicorp/terraform/commits/e865faf318950f4b86b15d2e56c4c3ec0667709a"}]

[{"sha":"b38e885409c02ee6a43604c3a9f37fc98e925315","author":{"name":"Revan Sopher","email":"fd8618e46eba31404d9f9c653310103aea3024f0@google.com"},"message":"Preserve TPUDistributedVariables passed to TPUStrategy.run().

Normally run() converts all inputs to Tensor, which uses the current value of a variable.
Disabling the cast doesn't work, as a lower MLIR op will cast the variable to Tensor anyway.
Instead we partially apply any TPUDistributedVariables to the function before replicating the remaining inputs.

This doesn't enable any new functionality per se, as it was always possible to implicitly capture the variables in the Python function, but this matches behavior to MirroredStrategy and avoids a simple usability issue.

Note that this change of behavior might break anyone who was relying on the automatic cast happening, in which case the user-side fix would be to manually cast.

Unique TensorFlower","email":"746aced590a184ef4169166e753f7c211e32e5fc@tensorflow.org"},"message":"Control dependency flowing between devices should have a higher priority virtual channel than data flows, otherwise there is a risk of control transfer getting stuck behind a large data transfer. Current channel device implementation is simple, it doesn't model such prioritization.

Instead of adding complexity to channel device, tf-sim could let control deps bypass channel device and (magically) flow across devices in zero time. Control deps are small, latency dominated transfers. Channel devices are only good at modeling BW bound transfers, so bypassing channel device for control deps should not be so bad.

Here we propagate in the initialized terminal.Streams from package main,
and then onwards to backends running in CLI mode.

This also replaces our use of helper/wrappedstreams to determine whether
stdin is a terminal or a pipe. helper/wrappedstreams returns incorrect
file descriptors on Windows, causing StdinPiped to always return false on
that platform and thus causing one of the odd behaviors discussed in

Finally, this includes some wrappers around the ability to look up the
number of columns in the terminal in preparation for use elsewhere. These
wrappers deal with the fact that our unit tests typically won't populate
meta.Streams.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/pecigonzalo/terraform/commits/d2c3403ab60e378f91ba49f70f08cbef720a5653"},{"sha":"e6a516d87e2f8a9b45102713142212296ed087bf","author":{"name":"Martin Atkins","email":"a1bdfbfb01322b54f9edf8cea8f328c9384b211a@degeneration.co.uk"},"message":"backend/local: Use terminal properties to tweak the plan output

We now require the output to accept UTF-8 and we can determine how wide
the terminal (if any) is, so here we begin to make use of that for the
"terraform plan" command.

The horizontal rule is now made of box drawing characters instead of
hyphens and fills the whole terminal width.

The paragraphs of text in the output are now also wrapped to fill the
terminal width, instead of the hard-wrapping we did before.

This is just a start down the road of making better use of the terminal
capabilities. Lots of other commands could benefit from updates like these
too.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/pecigonzalo/terraform/commits/e6a516d87e2f8a9b45102713142212296ed087bf"},{"sha":"0c84a56700a26fa766f58052497c3731328139db","author":{"name":"Martin Atkins","email":"a1bdfbfb01322b54f9edf8cea8f328c9384b211a@degeneration.co.uk"},"message":"command/format: Use box drawing chars for rules in diagnostics

We were previously using some ASCII art to create some visual divisions
between parts of the diagnostic output. Now that we are requiring a UTF-8
terminal we can print out box drawing characters instead.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/pecigonzalo/terraform/commits/0c84a56700a26fa766f58052497c3731328139db"},{"sha":"1f1af87dead21b9fbea31cb6a0563da1efd8bd62","author":{"name":"Martin Atkins","email":"a1bdfbfb01322b54f9edf8cea8f328c9384b211a@degeneration.co.uk"},"message":"command/format: Don't try to fill the last terminal column

In some terminal emulators, writing a character into the last column on a
row causes the terminal to immediately wrap to the beginning of the next
line, even if the very next character in the stream is a hard newline.
That can then lead to errant blank lines in the final output which make
it harder to navigate the visual hierarchy.

As a compromise to avoid this, we'll format our horizontal rules and
paragraphs to one column less than the terminal width. That does mean that
our horizontal rules won't _quite_ cover the whole terminal width, but
it seems like a good compromise in order to get consistent behavior across
a wider variety of terminal implementations.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/pecigonzalo/terraform/commits/1f1af87dead21b9fbea31cb6a0563da1efd8bd62"},{"sha":"296c48405bccba1a395a556810e1795829083164","author":{"name":"Martin Atkins","email":"a1bdfbfb01322b54f9edf8cea8f328c9384b211a@degeneration.co.uk"},"message":"Update CHANGELOG.md","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/pecigonzalo/terraform/commits/296c48405bccba1a395a556810e1795829083164"}]

PiperOrigin-RevId: 351710753
Change-Id: Id906c5a19e299a6236c28e8bc368b19d5e34a56e","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/Nicholas282787728/tensorflow/commits/a4c1164634eb754b5192586b9c24c4e95cda8b7c"},{"sha":"b38e885409c02ee6a43604c3a9f37fc98e925315","author":{"name":"Revan Sopher","email":"fd8618e46eba31404d9f9c653310103aea3024f0@google.com"},"message":"Preserve TPUDistributedVariables passed to TPUStrategy.run().

Normally run() converts all inputs to Tensor, which uses the current value of a variable.
Disabling the cast doesn't work, as a lower MLIR op will cast the variable to Tensor anyway.
Instead we partially apply any TPUDistributedVariables to the function before replicating the remaining inputs.

This doesn't enable any new functionality per se, as it was always possible to implicitly capture the variables in the Python function, but this matches behavior to MirroredStrategy and avoids a simple usability issue.

Note that this change of behavior might break anyone who was relying on the automatic cast happening, in which case the user-side fix would be to manually cast.

Change-Id: I6cf14701c300b599b8479831977c5654f04344e0","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/isanjit3/tensorflow/commits/e8f5a369d74455f3ae142ebfdc6b29939209ac3b"},{"sha":"8f556acfa1a6e58a0a59132469cca185df962b89","author":{"name":"Smit Hinsu","email":"0f9dce5f2da36d8473ff9a50fbb0e06a148c5fae@google.com"},"message":"Do not round trip to MLIR in the MLIR bridge if no TPUs are found

Currently, the filtering in the `IsEnabled` method doesn't inspect the devices but at the time of execution MLIR passes are skipped if there are no TPUs. This results in the conversion to MLIR and then back to GraphDef. This roundtrip does functionalization of control flow v1 and some other mutations so it is not idempotent.

Doing checks in the `IsEnabled` method will skip the unnecessary roundtrip.

PiperOrigin-RevId: 351822115
Change-Id: I423db3385e0b80709fc442d8c2991211186e4bcc","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/Nicholas282787728/tensorflow/commits/e687cab61615a95b8aea79120c9f168d4cc30955"},{"sha":"3d28cdc6032ef271510e85df9ab5f95a98f1c6a8","author":{"name":"Andrew Audibert","email":"23f2b5dd93c922fa4b806faa35ad0644038a966e@google.com"},"message":"[tf.data service] Improve cancellation for tf.data service requests.

1. If a DataServiceDataset iterator is cancelled, it will now call TryCancel on its outstanding RPCs.
2. As a result, we can reduce the frequency of returning from blocked round-robin requests to check whether the iterator is cancelled. This may avoid delays in GetNext() that could happen if one consumer reads from a round earlier than others, and needs to perform multiple retries with exponential backoff.
3. Because of (2), server shutdown may take up to 1 minute if a round-robin request is blocked waiting for other consumers. To prevent slow unit tests, certain tests store their servers globally so that they are destroyed immediately at process exit without waiting for their outstanding RPCs to finish.

Running data_service_ops_test.py locally, this CL reduces the time from 27 seconds to 20 seconds

Change-Id: Ib24db15f3d8c66a9bc1060ba951f3f930a346096","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/Nicholas282787728/tensorflow/commits/a70d68b3acb7c248572a9ce2e90a67392e6c689c"},{"sha":"3ca937c9ef47f662bc613b1086476b0b6f2042d8","author":{"name":"Christian Sigg","email":"bf0bb771be8a27677291ada19f594af5450440c6@google.com"},"message":"Add support for copybara inline directives in BUILD and .bzl files.

Open-source BUILD files are mapped to the Google-internal variants and vice-versa using a [copybara](https://github.com/google/copybara) workflow. This change adds a step to this workflow that allows inline directives to (un-)comment code:

```python
cc_binary(
    ...
    srcs = [
        "common_src.cc",
        # copybara:uncomment(<reason here>) "google_only_src.cc",
        "oss_only_src.cc",  # copybara:comment(<reason here>)
    ],
    deps = [
        ":common_dep",
        # copybara:uncomment_begin(<reason here>)
        # ":google_only_dep",
        # copybara:uncomment_end_and_comment_begin
        ":oss_only_dep",
        # copybara:comment_end
    ],
)
```

The intended use case is to encode relatively small one-off
differences between internal and OSS BUILD files. Making those differences
explicit and inline will hopefully help contributors to write PRs that don't trip up our internal build, and Googlers to write changes that don't break the OSS build.

[{"sha":"2d8d83951955f25c75716a1ed169990b1713b1f8","author":{"name":"j-bernardi","email":"c7fb1083a8e0e494f05049af5d8c1b0768ef2e84@gmail.com"},"message":"Adding multi_dim to class_weight option in fit()

Currently, model.fit(class_weight={}) only works if y_data is of
rank 2 in the output, e.g. (batch_size,) or (batch_size, N_one_hot)
(if N==1, squeeze).

This change adds a flag `class_weight_mode`="multi_dim" to
`model.compile()` that allows dense labels of any shape to be compatible
with `class_weight` in `model.fit()`, asserting that they are either
one_hot encoded or in dense representation with an expanded final
dimension. E.g. necessary for image segmentation or temporal / sequence
data. The relevant tests are included for the DataHandler.

If the provisioner configuration includes sensitive values, it's a
reasonable assumption that we should suppress its log output. Obvious
examples where this makes sense include echoing a secret to a file using
local-exec or remote-exec.

This commit adds tests for both logging output from provisioners with
non-sensitive configuration, and suppressing logs for provisioners with
sensitive values in configuration.

Note that we do not suppress logs if connection info contains sensitive
information, as provisioners should not be logging connection
information under any circumstances.","distinct":false,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/hashicorp/terraform/commits/4f53234d8cf6c9f964ac8bfa8bce3a624a119bf1"},{"sha":"e3804810a9c95fe590f6eb3807a12d86a0ecf76e","author":{"name":"James Bardin","email":"62973226c85cb5a1996aaed2ce372ac02dcad8b7@gmail.com"},"message":"Accept JSON encoded dynamic values from providers

More precise handling of lists and maps within sets for ProposedNewObject","distinct":false,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/hashicorp/terraform/commits/98dc3990628bb94f5877cd04e1cf56851ba8a7bb"},{"sha":"30204ecded21fb52c992b0a707bb4cbb96e2c608","author":{"name":"Martin Atkins","email":"a1bdfbfb01322b54f9edf8cea8f328c9384b211a@degeneration.co.uk"},"message":"command/cliconfig: Allow development overrides for providers

For normal provider installation we want to associate each provider with
a selected version number and find a suitable package for that version
that conforms to the official hashes for that release.

Those requirements are very onerous for a provider developer currently
testing a not-yet-released build, though. To allow for that case this new
CLI configuration feature allows overriding specific providers to refer
to give local filesystem directories.

Any provider overridden in this way is not subject to the usual
restrictions about selected versions or checksum conformance, and
activating an override won't cause any changes to the selections recorded
in the lock file because it's intended to be a temporary setting for one
developer only.

This is, in a sense, a spiritual successor of an old capability we had to
override specific plugins in the CLI configuration file. There were
some vestiges of that left in the main package and CLI config package
but nothing has actually been honoring them for several versions now and
so this commit removes them to avoid confusion with the new mechanism.","distinct":false,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/hashicorp/terraform/commits/30204ecded21fb52c992b0a707bb4cbb96e2c608"}]

[{"sha":"42e04b46d19648968537a404f15cebc42b6fab54","author":{"name":"Andrew Clark","email":"46f1a0bd5592a2f9244ca321b129902a06b53e03@andrewclark.io"},"message":"Fix: Detach deleted fiber's alternate, too (#20587)

We need to call `detachFiberAfterEffects` on the fiber's alternate to
clean it up. We're currently not, because the `alternate` field is
cleared during `detachFiberMutation`. So I deferred detaching the
`alternate` until the passive phase. Only the `return` pointer needs to
be detached for semantic purposes.

I don't think there's any good way to test this without using
reflection. It's not even observable using out our "supported"
reflection APIs (`findDOMNode`), or at least not that I can think of.
Which is a good thing, in a way.

It's not really a memory leak, either, because the only reference to the
alternate fiber is from the parent's alternate. Which will be
disconnected the next time the parent is updated or deleted.

It's really only observable if you mess around with internals in ways
you're not supposed to — I found it because a product test in www that
uses Enzyme was doing just that.

In lieu of a new unit test, I confirmed this patch fixes the broken
product test.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/gouda1a1/react/commits/42e04b46d19648968537a404f15cebc42b6fab54"},{"sha":"98313aaa7ea58d49eb30ecffc0f9eb6fc1ef467a","author":{"name":"Andrew Clark","email":"46f1a0bd5592a2f9244ca321b129902a06b53e03@andrewclark.io"},"message":"Migrate prepare-release-from-ci to new workflow (#20581)

* Migrate prepare-release-from-ci to new workflow

I added a `--releaseChannel (-r)` argument to script. You must choose
either "stable" or "experimental", because every build job now includes
both channels.

The prepare-release-from-npm script is unchanged since those releases
are downloaded from npm, nt CI.

(As a side note, I think we should start preparing semver releases using
the prepare-release-from-ci script, too, and get rid of
prepare-release-from-npm. I think that was a neat idea originally but
because we already run `npm pack` before storing the artifacts in CI,
there's really not much additional safety; the only safeguard it adds is
the requirement that a "next" release must have already been published.)

PiperOrigin-RevId: 351710753
Change-Id: Id906c5a19e299a6236c28e8bc368b19d5e34a56e","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/greedisgoood/tensorflow/commits/a4c1164634eb754b5192586b9c24c4e95cda8b7c"},{"sha":"b38e885409c02ee6a43604c3a9f37fc98e925315","author":{"name":"Revan Sopher","email":"fd8618e46eba31404d9f9c653310103aea3024f0@google.com"},"message":"Preserve TPUDistributedVariables passed to TPUStrategy.run().

Normally run() converts all inputs to Tensor, which uses the current value of a variable.
Disabling the cast doesn't work, as a lower MLIR op will cast the variable to Tensor anyway.
Instead we partially apply any TPUDistributedVariables to the function before replicating the remaining inputs.

This doesn't enable any new functionality per se, as it was always possible to implicitly capture the variables in the Python function, but this matches behavior to MirroredStrategy and avoids a simple usability issue.

Note that this change of behavior might break anyone who was relying on the automatic cast happening, in which case the user-side fix would be to manually cast.

Change-Id: Id906c5a19e299a6236c28e8bc368b19d5e34a56e","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/melG81/tensorflow/commits/a4c1164634eb754b5192586b9c24c4e95cda8b7c"},{"sha":"b38e885409c02ee6a43604c3a9f37fc98e925315","author":{"name":"Revan Sopher","email":"fd8618e46eba31404d9f9c653310103aea3024f0@google.com"},"message":"Preserve TPUDistributedVariables passed to TPUStrategy.run().

Normally run() converts all inputs to Tensor, which uses the current value of a variable.
Disabling the cast doesn't work, as a lower MLIR op will cast the variable to Tensor anyway.
Instead we partially apply any TPUDistributedVariables to the function before replicating the remaining inputs.

This doesn't enable any new functionality per se, as it was always possible to implicitly capture the variables in the Python function, but this matches behavior to MirroredStrategy and avoids a simple usability issue.

Note that this change of behavior might break anyone who was relying on the automatic cast happening, in which case the user-side fix would be to manually cast.

[{"sha":"42e04b46d19648968537a404f15cebc42b6fab54","author":{"name":"Andrew Clark","email":"46f1a0bd5592a2f9244ca321b129902a06b53e03@andrewclark.io"},"message":"Fix: Detach deleted fiber's alternate, too (#20587)

We need to call `detachFiberAfterEffects` on the fiber's alternate to
clean it up. We're currently not, because the `alternate` field is
cleared during `detachFiberMutation`. So I deferred detaching the
`alternate` until the passive phase. Only the `return` pointer needs to
be detached for semantic purposes.

I don't think there's any good way to test this without using
reflection. It's not even observable using out our "supported"
reflection APIs (`findDOMNode`), or at least not that I can think of.
Which is a good thing, in a way.

It's not really a memory leak, either, because the only reference to the
alternate fiber is from the parent's alternate. Which will be
disconnected the next time the parent is updated or deleted.

It's really only observable if you mess around with internals in ways
you're not supposed to — I found it because a product test in www that
uses Enzyme was doing just that.

In lieu of a new unit test, I confirmed this patch fixes the broken
product test.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/SimenB/react/commits/42e04b46d19648968537a404f15cebc42b6fab54"},{"sha":"98313aaa7ea58d49eb30ecffc0f9eb6fc1ef467a","author":{"name":"Andrew Clark","email":"46f1a0bd5592a2f9244ca321b129902a06b53e03@andrewclark.io"},"message":"Migrate prepare-release-from-ci to new workflow (#20581)

* Migrate prepare-release-from-ci to new workflow

I added a `--releaseChannel (-r)` argument to script. You must choose
either "stable" or "experimental", because every build job now includes
both channels.

The prepare-release-from-npm script is unchanged since those releases
are downloaded from npm, nt CI.

(As a side note, I think we should start preparing semver releases using
the prepare-release-from-ci script, too, and get rid of
prepare-release-from-npm. I think that was a neat idea originally but
because we already run `npm pack` before storing the artifacts in CI,
there's really not much additional safety; the only safeguard it adds is
the requirement that a "next" release must have already been published.)

* Move validation to parse-params module","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/SimenB/react/commits/98313aaa7ea58d49eb30ecffc0f9eb6fc1ef467a"}]

Change-Id: I423db3385e0b80709fc442d8c2991211186e4bcc","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/Rachelmorrell/tensorflow/commits/e687cab61615a95b8aea79120c9f168d4cc30955"},{"sha":"3d28cdc6032ef271510e85df9ab5f95a98f1c6a8","author":{"name":"Andrew Audibert","email":"23f2b5dd93c922fa4b806faa35ad0644038a966e@google.com"},"message":"[tf.data service] Improve cancellation for tf.data service requests.

1. If a DataServiceDataset iterator is cancelled, it will now call TryCancel on its outstanding RPCs.
2. As a result, we can reduce the frequency of returning from blocked round-robin requests to check whether the iterator is cancelled. This may avoid delays in GetNext() that could happen if one consumer reads from a round earlier than others, and needs to perform multiple retries with exponential backoff.
3. Because of (2), server shutdown may take up to 1 minute if a round-robin request is blocked waiting for other consumers. To prevent slow unit tests, certain tests store their servers globally so that they are destroyed immediately at process exit without waiting for their outstanding RPCs to finish.

Running data_service_ops_test.py locally, this CL reduces the time from 27 seconds to 20 seconds

Unique TensorFlower","email":"746aced590a184ef4169166e753f7c211e32e5fc@tensorflow.org"},"message":"Control dependency flowing between devices should have a higher priority virtual channel than data flows, otherwise there is a risk of control transfer getting stuck behind a large data transfer. Current channel device implementation is simple, it doesn't model such prioritization.

Instead of adding complexity to channel device, tf-sim could let control deps bypass channel device and (magically) flow across devices in zero time. Control deps are small, latency dominated transfers. Channel devices are only good at modeling BW bound transfers, so bypassing channel device for control deps should not be so bad.

I frequently see people attempting to ask questions about Terraform's
error and warning messages but either only copying part of the message or
accidentally copying a surrounding paragraph that isn't part of the
message.

While I'm sure some of these are just "careless" mistakes, I've also
noticed that this has sometimes overlapped with someone asking a question
whose answer is written directly in the part of the message they didn't
include when copying, and so I have a theory that our current output
doesn't create a good enough visual hierarchy for sighted users to
understand where the diagnostic messages start and end when we show them
in close proximity to other content, or to other diagnostic messages.
As a result, some folks fail to notice the relevant message that might've
answered their question.

I tried a few different experiments for different approaches here, such
as adding more horizontal rules to the output and coloring the detail
text differently, but the approach that felt like the nicest compromise
to me was what's implemented here, which is to add a vertical line
along the left edge of each diagnostic message, colored to match with the
typical color we use for each diagnostic severity. This means that the
diagnostics end up slightly indented from what's around them, and the
vertical line seems to help subtly signal how we intended the content
to be grouped together.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/hashicorp/terraform/commits/fd259fdc78c2a7ee0bd8a69891918e0cf18c984f"}]

Change-Id: I423db3385e0b80709fc442d8c2991211186e4bcc","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/melG81/tensorflow/commits/e687cab61615a95b8aea79120c9f168d4cc30955"},{"sha":"3d28cdc6032ef271510e85df9ab5f95a98f1c6a8","author":{"name":"Andrew Audibert","email":"23f2b5dd93c922fa4b806faa35ad0644038a966e@google.com"},"message":"[tf.data service] Improve cancellation for tf.data service requests.

1. If a DataServiceDataset iterator is cancelled, it will now call TryCancel on its outstanding RPCs.
2. As a result, we can reduce the frequency of returning from blocked round-robin requests to check whether the iterator is cancelled. This may avoid delays in GetNext() that could happen if one consumer reads from a round earlier than others, and needs to perform multiple retries with exponential backoff.
3. Because of (2), server shutdown may take up to 1 minute if a round-robin request is blocked waiting for other consumers. To prevent slow unit tests, certain tests store their servers globally so that they are destroyed immediately at process exit without waiting for their outstanding RPCs to finish.

Running data_service_ops_test.py locally, this CL reduces the time from 27 seconds to 20 seconds

PiperOrigin-RevId: 351822115
Change-Id: I423db3385e0b80709fc442d8c2991211186e4bcc","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/akram/tensorflow/commits/e687cab61615a95b8aea79120c9f168d4cc30955"},{"sha":"3d28cdc6032ef271510e85df9ab5f95a98f1c6a8","author":{"name":"Andrew Audibert","email":"23f2b5dd93c922fa4b806faa35ad0644038a966e@google.com"},"message":"[tf.data service] Improve cancellation for tf.data service requests.

1. If a DataServiceDataset iterator is cancelled, it will now call TryCancel on its outstanding RPCs.
2. As a result, we can reduce the frequency of returning from blocked round-robin requests to check whether the iterator is cancelled. This may avoid delays in GetNext() that could happen if one consumer reads from a round earlier than others, and needs to perform multiple retries with exponential backoff.
3. Because of (2), server shutdown may take up to 1 minute if a round-robin request is blocked waiting for other consumers. To prevent slow unit tests, certain tests store their servers globally so that they are destroyed immediately at process exit without waiting for their outstanding RPCs to finish.

Running data_service_ops_test.py locally, this CL reduces the time from 27 seconds to 20 seconds

PiperOrigin-RevId: 351837613
Change-Id: Ib24db15f3d8c66a9bc1060ba951f3f930a346096","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/akram/tensorflow/commits/a70d68b3acb7c248572a9ce2e90a67392e6c689c"},{"sha":"3ca937c9ef47f662bc613b1086476b0b6f2042d8","author":{"name":"Christian Sigg","email":"bf0bb771be8a27677291ada19f594af5450440c6@google.com"},"message":"Add support for copybara inline directives in BUILD and .bzl files.

Open-source BUILD files are mapped to the Google-internal variants and vice-versa using a [copybara](https://github.com/google/copybara) workflow. This change adds a step to this workflow that allows inline directives to (un-)comment code:

```python
cc_binary(
    ...
    srcs = [
        "common_src.cc",
        # copybara:uncomment(<reason here>) "google_only_src.cc",
        "oss_only_src.cc",  # copybara:comment(<reason here>)
    ],
    deps = [
        ":common_dep",
        # copybara:uncomment_begin(<reason here>)
        # ":google_only_dep",
        # copybara:uncomment_end_and_comment_begin
        ":oss_only_dep",
        # copybara:comment_end
    ],
)
```

The intended use case is to encode relatively small one-off
differences between internal and OSS BUILD files. Making those differences
explicit and inline will hopefully help contributors to write PRs that don't trip up our internal build, and Googlers to write changes that don't break the OSS build.

[{"sha":"42e04b46d19648968537a404f15cebc42b6fab54","author":{"name":"Andrew Clark","email":"46f1a0bd5592a2f9244ca321b129902a06b53e03@andrewclark.io"},"message":"Fix: Detach deleted fiber's alternate, too (#20587)

We need to call `detachFiberAfterEffects` on the fiber's alternate to
clean it up. We're currently not, because the `alternate` field is
cleared during `detachFiberMutation`. So I deferred detaching the
`alternate` until the passive phase. Only the `return` pointer needs to
be detached for semantic purposes.

I don't think there's any good way to test this without using
reflection. It's not even observable using out our "supported"
reflection APIs (`findDOMNode`), or at least not that I can think of.
Which is a good thing, in a way.

It's not really a memory leak, either, because the only reference to the
alternate fiber is from the parent's alternate. Which will be
disconnected the next time the parent is updated or deleted.

It's really only observable if you mess around with internals in ways
you're not supposed to — I found it because a product test in www that
uses Enzyme was doing just that.

In lieu of a new unit test, I confirmed this patch fixes the broken

The prepare-release-from-npm script is unchanged since those releases

Unique TensorFlower","email":"746aced590a184ef4169166e753f7c211e32e5fc@tensorflow.org"},"message":"Control dependency flowing between devices should have a higher priority virtual channel than data flows, otherwise there is a risk of control transfer getting stuck behind a large data transfer. Current channel device implementation is simple, it doesn't model such prioritization.

Instead of adding complexity to channel device, tf-sim could let control deps bypass channel device and (magically) flow across devices in zero time. Control deps are small, latency dominated transfers. Channel devices are only good at modeling BW bound transfers, so bypassing channel device for control deps should not be so bad.

This also replaces our use of helper/wrappedstreams to determine whether
stdin is a terminal or a pipe. helper/wrappedstreams returns incorrect
file descriptors on Windows, causing StdinPiped to always return false on
that platform and thus causing one of the odd behaviors discussed in

Finally, this includes some wrappers around the ability to look up the

wrappers deal with the fact that our unit tests typically won't populate
meta.Streams.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/Skarlso/terraform/commits/d2c3403ab60e378f91ba49f70f08cbef720a5653"},{"sha":"e6a516d87e2f8a9b45102713142212296ed087bf","author":{"name":"Martin Atkins","email":"a1bdfbfb01322b54f9edf8cea8f328c9384b211a@degeneration.co.uk"},"message":"backend/local: Use terminal properties to tweak the plan output

We now require the output to accept UTF-8 and we can determine how wide
the terminal (if any) is, so here we begin to make use of that for the
"terraform plan" command.

The horizontal rule is now made of box drawing characters instead of
hyphens and fills the whole terminal width.

The paragraphs of text in the output are now also wrapped to fill the
terminal width, instead of the hard-wrapping we did before.

This is just a start down the road of making better use of the terminal
capabilities. Lots of other commands could benefit from updates like these

We were previously using some ASCII art to create some visual divisions
between parts of the diagnostic output. Now that we are requiring a UTF-8
terminal we can print out box drawing characters instead.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/Skarlso/terraform/commits/0c84a56700a26fa766f58052497c3731328139db"},{"sha":"1f1af87dead21b9fbea31cb6a0563da1efd8bd62","author":{"name":"Martin Atkins","email":"a1bdfbfb01322b54f9edf8cea8f328c9384b211a@degeneration.co.uk"},"message":"command/format: Don't try to fill the last terminal column

In some terminal emulators, writing a character into the last column on a
row causes the terminal to immediately wrap to the beginning of the next
line, even if the very next character in the stream is a hard newline.
That can then lead to errant blank lines in the final output which make
it harder to navigate the visual hierarchy.

As a compromise to avoid this, we'll format our horizontal rules and
paragraphs to one column less than the terminal width. That does mean that
our horizontal rules won't _quite_ cover the whole terminal width, but
it seems like a good compromise in order to get consistent behavior across
a wider variety of terminal implementations.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/Skarlso/terraform/commits/1f1af87dead21b9fbea31cb6a0563da1efd8bd62"},{"sha":"296c48405bccba1a395a556810e1795829083164","author":{"name":"Martin Atkins","email":"a1bdfbfb01322b54f9edf8cea8f328c9384b211a@degeneration.co.uk"},"message":"Update CHANGELOG.md","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/Skarlso/terraform/commits/296c48405bccba1a395a556810e1795829083164"}]

I added a `--releaseChannel (-r)` argument to script. You must choose
either "stable" or "experimental", because every build job now includes
both channels.

The prepare-release-from-npm script is unchanged since those releases
are downloaded from npm, nt CI.

(As a side note, I think we should start preparing semver releases using
the prepare-release-from-ci script, too, and get rid of
prepare-release-from-npm. I think that was a neat idea originally but
because we already run `npm pack` before storing the artifacts in CI,
there's really not much additional safety; the only safeguard it adds is
the requirement that a "next" release must have already been published.)

[{"sha":"e522991c4172021e5d46c9ff4c3829eff2f57b0d","author":{"name":"Andrew Clark","email":"46f1a0bd5592a2f9244ca321b129902a06b53e03@andrewclark.io"},"message":"Fix: Detach deleted fiber's alternate, too

We need to call `detachFiberAfterEffects` on the fiber's alternate to
clean it up. We're currently not, because the `alternate` field is
cleared during `detachFiberMutation`. So I deferred detaching the
`alternate` until the passive phase. Only the `return` pointer needs to
be detached for semantic purposes.

I don't think there's any good way to test this without using
reflection. It's not even observable using out our "supported"
reflection APIs (`findDOMNode`), or at least not that I can think of.
Which is a good thing, in a way.

It's not really a memory leak, either, because the only reference to the
alternate fiber is from the parent's alternate. Which will be
disconnected the next time the parent is updated or deleted.

It's really only observable if you mess around with internals in ways
you're not supposed to — I found it because a product test in www that
uses Enzyme was doing just that.

In lieu of a new unit test, I confirmed this patch fixes the broken
product test.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/acdlite/react/commits/e522991c4172021e5d46c9ff4c3829eff2f57b0d"}]

Change-Id: I6cf14701c300b599b8479831977c5654f04344e0","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/kokizzu/tensorflow/commits/e8f5a369d74455f3ae142ebfdc6b29939209ac3b"},{"sha":"8f556acfa1a6e58a0a59132469cca185df962b89","author":{"name":"Smit Hinsu","email":"0f9dce5f2da36d8473ff9a50fbb0e06a148c5fae@google.com"},"message":"Do not round trip to MLIR in the MLIR bridge if no TPUs are found

Currently, the filtering in the `IsEnabled` method doesn't inspect the devices but at the time of execution MLIR passes are skipped if there are no TPUs. This results in the conversion to MLIR and then back to GraphDef. This roundtrip does functionalization of control flow v1 and some other mutations so it is not idempotent.

Doing checks in the `IsEnabled` method will skip the unnecessary roundtrip.

Change-Id: I423db3385e0b80709fc442d8c2991211186e4bcc","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/xiaoxiaopingzi/tensorflow/commits/e687cab61615a95b8aea79120c9f168d4cc30955"},{"sha":"3d28cdc6032ef271510e85df9ab5f95a98f1c6a8","author":{"name":"Andrew Audibert","email":"23f2b5dd93c922fa4b806faa35ad0644038a966e@google.com"},"message":"[tf.data service] Improve cancellation for tf.data service requests.

1. If a DataServiceDataset iterator is cancelled, it will now call TryCancel on its outstanding RPCs.
2. As a result, we can reduce the frequency of returning from blocked round-robin requests to check whether the iterator is cancelled. This may avoid delays in GetNext() that could happen if one consumer reads from a round earlier than others, and needs to perform multiple retries with exponential backoff.
3. Because of (2), server shutdown may take up to 1 minute if a round-robin request is blocked waiting for other consumers. To prevent slow unit tests, certain tests store their servers globally so that they are destroyed immediately at process exit without waiting for their outstanding RPCs to finish.

Running data_service_ops_test.py locally, this CL reduces the time from 27 seconds to 20 seconds

PiperOrigin-RevId: 351837613
Change-Id: Ib24db15f3d8c66a9bc1060ba951f3f930a346096","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/xiaoxiaopingzi/tensorflow/commits/a70d68b3acb7c248572a9ce2e90a67392e6c689c"},{"sha":"3ca937c9ef47f662bc613b1086476b0b6f2042d8","author":{"name":"Christian Sigg","email":"bf0bb771be8a27677291ada19f594af5450440c6@google.com"},"message":"Add support for copybara inline directives in BUILD and .bzl files.

Open-source BUILD files are mapped to the Google-internal variants and vice-versa using a [copybara](https://github.com/google/copybara) workflow. This change adds a step to this workflow that allows inline directives to (un-)comment code:

```python
cc_binary(
    ...
    srcs = [
        "common_src.cc",
        # copybara:uncomment(<reason here>) "google_only_src.cc",
        "oss_only_src.cc",  # copybara:comment(<reason here>)
    ],
    deps = [
        ":common_dep",
        # copybara:uncomment_begin(<reason here>)
        # ":google_only_dep",
        # copybara:uncomment_end_and_comment_begin
        ":oss_only_dep",
        # copybara:comment_end
    ],
)
```

The intended use case is to encode relatively small one-off
differences between internal and OSS BUILD files. Making those differences
explicit and inline will hopefully help contributors to write PRs that don't trip up our internal build, and Googlers to write changes that don't break the OSS build.

Because the destroy plan only creates the necessary changes for apply to
remove all the resources, it does no reading of resources or data
sources, leading to stale data in the state. In most cases this is not a
problem, but when a provider configuration is using resource values, the
provider may not be able to run correctly during apply. In prior
versions of terraform, the implicit refresh that happened during
`terraform destroy` would update the data sources and remove missing
resources from state as required.

The destroy plan graph has a minimal amount of information, so it is not
feasible to work the reading of resources into the operation without
completely replicating the normal plan graph, and updating the plan
graph and all destroy node implementation is also a considerable amount
of refactoring. Instead, we can run a normal plan which is used to
refresh the state before creating the destroy plan. This brings back
similar behavior to core versions prior to 0.14, and the refresh can
still be skipped using the `-refresh=false` cli flag.","distinct":false,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/hashicorp/terraform/commits/0b3b84acc1ade2e394fcb7e3b956bf2ea0789eb1"},{"sha":"e614fb9aed597252e6ca18244ca779e0d61d3683","author":{"name":"James Bardin","email":"62973226c85cb5a1996aaed2ce372ac02dcad8b7@gmail.com"},"message":"refresh is expected for destroy

Using the latest version of HiFi 4 NN Library.
This version has optimized implementation of FC and softmax for int8 datatype (not yet integrated).
Tested the change using following commands:
make -f tensorflow/lite/micro/tools/make/Makefile TARGET=xtensa OPTIMIZED_KERNEL_DIR=xtensa TARGET_ARCH=hifi4 XTENSA_TOOLS_VERSION=RI-2020.5-linux XTENSA_CORE=AE_HiFi4_LE5_FP_XC clean_downloads
make -f tensorflow/lite/micro/tools/make/Makefile TARGET=xtensa OPTIMIZED_KERNEL_DIR=xtensa TARGET_ARCH=hifi4 XTENSA_TOOLS_VERSION=RI-2020.5-linux XTENSA_CORE=AE_HiFi4_LE5_FP_XC test_kernel_softmax_test","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/xiaohanhuang/tensorflow/commits/e4fbfe63f6a27f28d5210d4a72c638c2b7ab41e6"},{"sha":"8f556acfa1a6e58a0a59132469cca185df962b89","author":{"name":"Smit Hinsu","email":"0f9dce5f2da36d8473ff9a50fbb0e06a148c5fae@google.com"},"message":"Do not round trip to MLIR in the MLIR bridge if no TPUs are found

Currently, the filtering in the `IsEnabled` method doesn't inspect the devices but at the time of execution MLIR passes are skipped if there are no TPUs. This results in the conversion to MLIR and then back to GraphDef. This roundtrip does functionalization of control flow v1 and some other mutations so it is not idempotent.

Doing checks in the `IsEnabled` method will skip the unnecessary roundtrip.

Unique TensorFlower","email":"746aced590a184ef4169166e753f7c211e32e5fc@tensorflow.org"},"message":"Control dependency flowing between devices should have a higher priority virtual channel than data flows, otherwise there is a risk of control transfer getting stuck behind a large data transfer. Current channel device implementation is simple, it doesn't model such prioritization.

Instead of adding complexity to channel device, tf-sim could let control deps bypass channel device and (magically) flow across devices in zero time. Control deps are small, latency dominated transfers. Channel devices are only good at modeling BW bound transfers, so bypassing channel device for control deps should not be so bad.

PiperOrigin-RevId: 351822115
Change-Id: I423db3385e0b80709fc442d8c2991211186e4bcc","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/Mu-L/tensorflow/commits/e687cab61615a95b8aea79120c9f168d4cc30955"},{"sha":"3d28cdc6032ef271510e85df9ab5f95a98f1c6a8","author":{"name":"Andrew Audibert","email":"23f2b5dd93c922fa4b806faa35ad0644038a966e@google.com"},"message":"[tf.data service] Improve cancellation for tf.data service requests.

1. If a DataServiceDataset iterator is cancelled, it will now call TryCancel on its outstanding RPCs.
2. As a result, we can reduce the frequency of returning from blocked round-robin requests to check whether the iterator is cancelled. This may avoid delays in GetNext() that could happen if one consumer reads from a round earlier than others, and needs to perform multiple retries with exponential backoff.
3. Because of (2), server shutdown may take up to 1 minute if a round-robin request is blocked waiting for other consumers. To prevent slow unit tests, certain tests store their servers globally so that they are destroyed immediately at process exit without waiting for their outstanding RPCs to finish.

Running data_service_ops_test.py locally, this CL reduces the time from 27 seconds to 20 seconds

Change-Id: Ib24db15f3d8c66a9bc1060ba951f3f930a346096","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/Mu-L/tensorflow/commits/a70d68b3acb7c248572a9ce2e90a67392e6c689c"},{"sha":"3ca937c9ef47f662bc613b1086476b0b6f2042d8","author":{"name":"Christian Sigg","email":"bf0bb771be8a27677291ada19f594af5450440c6@google.com"},"message":"Add support for copybara inline directives in BUILD and .bzl files.

Open-source BUILD files are mapped to the Google-internal variants and vice-versa using a [copybara](https://github.com/google/copybara) workflow. This change adds a step to this workflow that allows inline directives to (un-)comment code:

```python
cc_binary(
    ...
    srcs = [
        "common_src.cc",
        # copybara:uncomment(<reason here>) "google_only_src.cc",
        "oss_only_src.cc",  # copybara:comment(<reason here>)
    ],
    deps = [
        ":common_dep",
        # copybara:uncomment_begin(<reason here>)
        # ":google_only_dep",
        # copybara:uncomment_end_and_comment_begin
        ":oss_only_dep",
        # copybara:comment_end
    ],
)
```

The intended use case is to encode relatively small one-off
differences between internal and OSS BUILD files. Making those differences
explicit and inline will hopefully help contributors to write PRs that don't trip up our internal build, and Googlers to write changes that don't break the OSS build.

Change-Id: Id906c5a19e299a6236c28e8bc368b19d5e34a56e","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/huaxz1986/tensorflow/commits/a4c1164634eb754b5192586b9c24c4e95cda8b7c"},{"sha":"b38e885409c02ee6a43604c3a9f37fc98e925315","author":{"name":"Revan Sopher","email":"fd8618e46eba31404d9f9c653310103aea3024f0@google.com"},"message":"Preserve TPUDistributedVariables passed to TPUStrategy.run().

Normally run() converts all inputs to Tensor, which uses the current value of a variable.
Disabling the cast doesn't work, as a lower MLIR op will cast the variable to Tensor anyway.
Instead we partially apply any TPUDistributedVariables to the function before replicating the remaining inputs.

This doesn't enable any new functionality per se, as it was always possible to implicitly capture the variables in the Python function, but this matches behavior to MirroredStrategy and avoids a simple usability issue.

Note that this change of behavior might break anyone who was relying on the automatic cast happening, in which case the user-side fix would be to manually cast.

```python
        ":oss_only_dep",
        # copybara:comment_end
    ],
)
```

The intended use case is to encode relatively small one-off
differences between internal and OSS BUILD files. Making those differences
explicit and inline will hopefully help contributors to write PRs that don't trip up our internal build, and Googlers to write changes that don't break the OSS build.

Unique TensorFlower","email":"746aced590a184ef4169166e753f7c211e32e5fc@tensorflow.org"},"message":"Control dependency flowing between devices should have a higher priority virtual channel than data flows, otherwise there is a risk of control transfer getting stuck behind a large data transfer. Current channel device implementation is simple, it doesn't model such prioritization.

Instead of adding complexity to channel device, tf-sim could let control deps bypass channel device and (magically) flow across devices in zero time. Control deps are small, latency dominated transfers. Channel devices are only good at modeling BW bound transfers, so bypassing channel device for control deps should not be so bad.

PiperOrigin-RevId: 351710753
Change-Id: Id906c5a19e299a6236c28e8bc368b19d5e34a56e","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/UofT-EcoSystem/tensorflow/commits/a4c1164634eb754b5192586b9c24c4e95cda8b7c"},{"sha":"b38e885409c02ee6a43604c3a9f37fc98e925315","author":{"name":"Revan Sopher","email":"fd8618e46eba31404d9f9c653310103aea3024f0@google.com"},"message":"Preserve TPUDistributedVariables passed to TPUStrategy.run().

Normally run() converts all inputs to Tensor, which uses the current value of a variable.
Disabling the cast doesn't work, as a lower MLIR op will cast the variable to Tensor anyway.
Instead we partially apply any TPUDistributedVariables to the function before replicating the remaining inputs.

This doesn't enable any new functionality per se, as it was always possible to implicitly capture the variables in the Python function, but this matches behavior to MirroredStrategy and avoids a simple usability issue.

Note that this change of behavior might break anyone who was relying on the automatic cast happening, in which case the user-side fix would be to manually cast.

Change-Id: I423db3385e0b80709fc442d8c2991211186e4bcc","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/xiaohanhuang/tensorflow/commits/e687cab61615a95b8aea79120c9f168d4cc30955"},{"sha":"3d28cdc6032ef271510e85df9ab5f95a98f1c6a8","author":{"name":"Andrew Audibert","email":"23f2b5dd93c922fa4b806faa35ad0644038a966e@google.com"},"message":"[tf.data service] Improve cancellation for tf.data service requests.

1. If a DataServiceDataset iterator is cancelled, it will now call TryCancel on its outstanding RPCs.
2. As a result, we can reduce the frequency of returning from blocked round-robin requests to check whether the iterator is cancelled. This may avoid delays in GetNext() that could happen if one consumer reads from a round earlier than others, and needs to perform multiple retries with exponential backoff.
3. Because of (2), server shutdown may take up to 1 minute if a round-robin request is blocked waiting for other consumers. To prevent slow unit tests, certain tests store their servers globally so that they are destroyed immediately at process exit without waiting for their outstanding RPCs to finish.

Running data_service_ops_test.py locally, this CL reduces the time from 27 seconds to 20 seconds

PiperOrigin-RevId: 351837613
Change-Id: Ib24db15f3d8c66a9bc1060ba951f3f930a346096","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/melG81/tensorflow/commits/a70d68b3acb7c248572a9ce2e90a67392e6c689c"},{"sha":"3ca937c9ef47f662bc613b1086476b0b6f2042d8","author":{"name":"Christian Sigg","email":"bf0bb771be8a27677291ada19f594af5450440c6@google.com"},"message":"Add support for copybara inline directives in BUILD and .bzl files.

Open-source BUILD files are mapped to the Google-internal variants and vice-versa using a [copybara](https://github.com/google/copybara) workflow. This change adds a step to this workflow that allows inline directives to (un-)comment code:

```python
cc_binary(
    ...
    srcs = [
        "common_src.cc",
        # copybara:uncomment(<reason here>) "google_only_src.cc",
        "oss_only_src.cc",  # copybara:comment(<reason here>)
    ],
    deps = [
        ":common_dep",
        # copybara:uncomment_begin(<reason here>)
        # ":google_only_dep",
        # copybara:uncomment_end_and_comment_begin
        ":oss_only_dep",
        # copybara:comment_end
    ],
)
```

The intended use case is to encode relatively small one-off
differences between internal and OSS BUILD files. Making those differences
explicit and inline will hopefully help contributors to write PRs that don't trip up our internal build, and Googlers to write changes that don't break the OSS build.

[{"sha":"3ca937c9ef47f662bc613b1086476b0b6f2042d8","author":{"name":"Christian Sigg","email":"bf0bb771be8a27677291ada19f594af5450440c6@google.com"},"message":"Add support for copybara inline directives in BUILD and .bzl files.

Open-source BUILD files are mapped to the Google-internal variants and vice-versa using a [copybara](https://github.com/google/copybara) workflow. This change adds a step to this workflow that allows inline directives to (un-)comment code:

```python
cc_binary(
    ...
    srcs = [
        "common_src.cc",
        # copybara:uncomment(<reason here>) "google_only_src.cc",
        "oss_only_src.cc",  # copybara:comment(<reason here>)
    ],
    deps = [
        ":common_dep",
        # copybara:uncomment_begin(<reason here>)
        # ":google_only_dep",
        # copybara:uncomment_end_and_comment_begin
        ":oss_only_dep",
        # copybara:comment_end
    ],
)
```

The intended use case is to encode relatively small one-off
differences between internal and OSS BUILD files. Making those differences
explicit and inline will hopefully help contributors to write PRs that don't trip up our internal build, and Googlers to write changes that don't break the OSS build.

Change-Id: Id906c5a19e299a6236c28e8bc368b19d5e34a56e","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/Rachelmorrell/tensorflow/commits/a4c1164634eb754b5192586b9c24c4e95cda8b7c"},{"sha":"b38e885409c02ee6a43604c3a9f37fc98e925315","author":{"name":"Revan Sopher","email":"fd8618e46eba31404d9f9c653310103aea3024f0@google.com"},"message":"Preserve TPUDistributedVariables passed to TPUStrategy.run().

Normally run() converts all inputs to Tensor, which uses the current value of a variable.
Disabling the cast doesn't work, as a lower MLIR op will cast the variable to Tensor anyway.
Instead we partially apply any TPUDistributedVariables to the function before replicating the remaining inputs.

This doesn't enable any new functionality per se, as it was always possible to implicitly capture the variables in the Python function, but this matches behavior to MirroredStrategy and avoids a simple usability issue.

Note that this change of behavior might break anyone who was relying on the automatic cast happening, in which case the user-side fix would be to manually cast.

[{"sha":"3d28cdc6032ef271510e85df9ab5f95a98f1c6a8","author":{"name":"Andrew Audibert","email":"23f2b5dd93c922fa4b806faa35ad0644038a966e@google.com"},"message":"[tf.data service] Improve cancellation for tf.data service requests.

1. If a DataServiceDataset iterator is cancelled, it will now call TryCancel on its outstanding RPCs.
2. As a result, we can reduce the frequency of returning from blocked round-robin requests to check whether the iterator is cancelled. This may avoid delays in GetNext() that could happen if one consumer reads from a round earlier than others, and needs to perform multiple retries with exponential backoff.
3. Because of (2), server shutdown may take up to 1 minute if a round-robin request is blocked waiting for other consumers. To prevent slow unit tests, certain tests store their servers globally so that they are destroyed immediately at process exit without waiting for their outstanding RPCs to finish.

Running data_service_ops_test.py locally, this CL reduces the time from 27 seconds to 20 seconds

Change-Id: Id906c5a19e299a6236c28e8bc368b19d5e34a56e","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/mark0725/tensorflow/commits/a4c1164634eb754b5192586b9c24c4e95cda8b7c"},{"sha":"b38e885409c02ee6a43604c3a9f37fc98e925315","author":{"name":"Revan Sopher","email":"fd8618e46eba31404d9f9c653310103aea3024f0@google.com"},"message":"Preserve TPUDistributedVariables passed to TPUStrategy.run().

Normally run() converts all inputs to Tensor, which uses the current value of a variable.
Disabling the cast doesn't work, as a lower MLIR op will cast the variable to Tensor anyway.
Instead we partially apply any TPUDistributedVariables to the function before replicating the remaining inputs.

This doesn't enable any new functionality per se, as it was always possible to implicitly capture the variables in the Python function, but this matches behavior to MirroredStrategy and avoids a simple usability issue.

Note that this change of behavior might break anyone who was relying on the automatic cast happening, in which case the user-side fix would be to manually cast.

[{"sha":"42e04b46d19648968537a404f15cebc42b6fab54","author":{"name":"Andrew Clark","email":"46f1a0bd5592a2f9244ca321b129902a06b53e03@andrewclark.io"},"message":"Fix: Detach deleted fiber's alternate, too (#20587)

We need to call `detachFiberAfterEffects` on the fiber's alternate to
clean it up. We're currently not, because the `alternate` field is
cleared during `detachFiberMutation`. So I deferred detaching the
`alternate` until the passive phase. Only the `return` pointer needs to
be detached for semantic purposes.

I don't think there's any good way to test this without using
reflection. It's not even observable using out our "supported"
reflection APIs (`findDOMNode`), or at least not that I can think of.
Which is a good thing, in a way.

It's not really a memory leak, either, because the only reference to the
alternate fiber is from the parent's alternate. Which will be
disconnected the next time the parent is updated or deleted.

It's really only observable if you mess around with internals in ways
you're not supposed to — I found it because a product test in www that
uses Enzyme was doing just that.

In lieu of a new unit test, I confirmed this patch fixes the broken
product test.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/db-apps/react/commits/42e04b46d19648968537a404f15cebc42b6fab54"}]

If provisioner configuration or connection info includes sensitive
values, we need to unmark them before calling the provisioner. Failing
to do so causes serialization to error.

Unlike resources, we do not need to capture marked paths here, so we
just discard the marks.","distinct":false,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/hashicorp/terraform/commits/9c580335e303610f96e01cfa8859ea6ee78ea87e"},{"sha":"4f53234d8cf6c9f964ac8bfa8bce3a624a119bf1","author":{"name":"Alisdair McDiarmid","email":"87d32f97664e6609e4bd0bde109443ba47829a78@users.noreply.github.com"},"message":"terraform: Hide maybe-sensitive provisioner output

If the provisioner configuration includes sensitive values, it's a
reasonable assumption that we should suppress its log output. Obvious
examples where this makes sense include echoing a secret to a file using
local-exec or remote-exec.

This commit adds tests for both logging output from provisioners with
non-sensitive configuration, and suppressing logs for provisioners with
sensitive values in configuration.

Note that we do not suppress logs if connection info contains sensitive
information, as provisioners should not be logging connection
information under any circumstances.","distinct":false,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/hashicorp/terraform/commits/4f53234d8cf6c9f964ac8bfa8bce3a624a119bf1"},{"sha":"e3804810a9c95fe590f6eb3807a12d86a0ecf76e","author":{"name":"James Bardin","email":"62973226c85cb5a1996aaed2ce372ac02dcad8b7@gmail.com"},"message":"Accept JSON encoded dynamic values from providers

Core was previously ignoring JSON-encoded dynamic values, but these are
technically supported, so we must either error or accept the value.
Since we already have the decoder for Json state, it's minimal effort to
support this on all plugin methods too.

This change also gives providers an easy way to implement the
UpgradeResourceState method. The obvious implementation of returning the same
JSON-encoded value has tripped up a few providers not using the legacy
SDK already, and we should have at least indicated that the value was
being lost.","distinct":false,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/hashicorp/terraform/commits/e3804810a9c95fe590f6eb3807a12d86a0ecf76e"},{"sha":"98dc3990628bb94f5877cd04e1cf56851ba8a7bb","author":{"name":"James Bardin","email":"62973226c85cb5a1996aaed2ce372ac02dcad8b7@gmail.com"},"message":"Merge pull request #26606 from hashicorp/jbardin/proposed-set-comparison

More precise handling of lists and maps within sets for ProposedNewObject","distinct":false,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/hashicorp/terraform/commits/98dc3990628bb94f5877cd04e1cf56851ba8a7bb"},{"sha":"30204ecded21fb52c992b0a707bb4cbb96e2c608","author":{"name":"Martin Atkins","email":"a1bdfbfb01322b54f9edf8cea8f328c9384b211a@degeneration.co.uk"},"message":"command/cliconfig: Allow development overrides for providers

For normal provider installation we want to associate each provider with
a selected version number and find a suitable package for that version
that conforms to the official hashes for that release.

Those requirements are very onerous for a provider developer currently
testing a not-yet-released build, though. To allow for that case this new
CLI configuration feature allows overriding specific providers to refer
to give local filesystem directories.

Any provider overridden in this way is not subject to the usual
restrictions about selected versions or checksum conformance, and
activating an override won't cause any changes to the selections recorded
in the lock file because it's intended to be a temporary setting for one
developer only.

This is, in a sense, a spiritual successor of an old capability we had to
override specific plugins in the CLI configuration file. There were
some vestiges of that left in the main package and CLI config package
but nothing has actually been honoring them for several versions now and
so this commit removes them to avoid confusion with the new mechanism.","distinct":false,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/hashicorp/terraform/commits/30204ecded21fb52c992b0a707bb4cbb96e2c608"}]

[{"sha":"42e04b46d19648968537a404f15cebc42b6fab54","author":{"name":"Andrew Clark","email":"46f1a0bd5592a2f9244ca321b129902a06b53e03@andrewclark.io"},"message":"Fix: Detach deleted fiber's alternate, too (#20587)

We need to call `detachFiberAfterEffects` on the fiber's alternate to
clean it up. We're currently not, because the `alternate` field is
cleared during `detachFiberMutation`. So I deferred detaching the
`alternate` until the passive phase. Only the `return` pointer needs to
be detached for semantic purposes.

I don't think there's any good way to test this without using
reflection. It's not even observable using out our "supported"
reflection APIs (`findDOMNode`), or at least not that I can think of.
Which is a good thing, in a way.

It's not really a memory leak, either, because the only reference to the
alternate fiber is from the parent's alternate. Which will be
disconnected the next time the parent is updated or deleted.

It's really only observable if you mess around with internals in ways
you're not supposed to — I found it because a product test in www that
uses Enzyme was doing just that.

In lieu of a new unit test, I confirmed this patch fixes the broken
product test.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/facebook/react/commits/42e04b46d19648968537a404f15cebc42b6fab54"}]

Change-Id: Ib24db15f3d8c66a9bc1060ba951f3f930a346096","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/kokizzu/tensorflow/commits/a70d68b3acb7c248572a9ce2e90a67392e6c689c"},{"sha":"3ca937c9ef47f662bc613b1086476b0b6f2042d8","author":{"name":"Christian Sigg","email":"bf0bb771be8a27677291ada19f594af5450440c6@google.com"},"message":"Add support for copybara inline directives in BUILD and .bzl files.

Open-source BUILD files are mapped to the Google-internal variants and vice-versa using a [copybara](https://github.com/google/copybara) workflow. This change adds a step to this workflow that allows inline directives to (un-)comment code:

```python
cc_binary(
    ...
    srcs = [
        "common_src.cc",
        # copybara:uncomment(<reason here>) "google_only_src.cc",
        "oss_only_src.cc",  # copybara:comment(<reason here>)
    ],
    deps = [
        ":common_dep",
        # copybara:uncomment_begin(<reason here>)
        # ":google_only_dep",
        # copybara:uncomment_end_and_comment_begin
        ":oss_only_dep",
        # copybara:comment_end
    ],
)
```

The intended use case is to encode relatively small one-off
differences between internal and OSS BUILD files. Making those differences
explicit and inline will hopefully help contributors to write PRs that don't trip up our internal build, and Googlers to write changes that don't break the OSS build.

Unique TensorFlower","email":"746aced590a184ef4169166e753f7c211e32e5fc@tensorflow.org"},"message":"Control dependency flowing between devices should have a higher priority virtual channel than data flows, otherwise there is a risk of control transfer getting stuck behind a large data transfer. Current channel device implementation is simple, it doesn't model such prioritization.

Instead of adding complexity to channel device, tf-sim could let control deps bypass channel device and (magically) flow across devices in zero time. Control deps are small, latency dominated transfers. Channel devices are only good at modeling BW bound transfers, so bypassing channel device for control deps should not be so bad.

Finally, this includes some wrappers around the ability to look up the

We now require the output to accept UTF-8 and we can determine how wide
the terminal (if any) is, so here we begin to make use of that for the
"terraform plan" command.

The horizontal rule is now made of box drawing characters instead of
hyphens and fills the whole terminal width.

The paragraphs of text in the output are now also wrapped to fill the

This is just a start down the road of making better use of the terminal

We were previously using some ASCII art to create some visual divisions
between parts of the diagnostic output. Now that we are requiring a UTF-8
terminal we can print out box drawing characters instead.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/tokyo2006/terraform/commits/0c84a56700a26fa766f58052497c3731328139db"},{"sha":"1f1af87dead21b9fbea31cb6a0563da1efd8bd62","author":{"name":"Martin Atkins","email":"a1bdfbfb01322b54f9edf8cea8f328c9384b211a@degeneration.co.uk"},"message":"command/format: Don't try to fill the last terminal column

In some terminal emulators, writing a character into the last column on a
row causes the terminal to immediately wrap to the beginning of the next
line, even if the very next character in the stream is a hard newline.
That can then lead to errant blank lines in the final output which make
it harder to navigate the visual hierarchy.

As a compromise to avoid this, we'll format our horizontal rules and
paragraphs to one column less than the terminal width. That does mean that
our horizontal rules won't _quite_ cover the whole terminal width, but
it seems like a good compromise in order to get consistent behavior across
a wider variety of terminal implementations.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/tokyo2006/terraform/commits/1f1af87dead21b9fbea31cb6a0563da1efd8bd62"},{"sha":"296c48405bccba1a395a556810e1795829083164","author":{"name":"Martin Atkins","email":"a1bdfbfb01322b54f9edf8cea8f328c9384b211a@degeneration.co.uk"},"message":"Update CHANGELOG.md","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/tokyo2006/terraform/commits/296c48405bccba1a395a556810e1795829083164"}]

PiperOrigin-RevId: 351837613
Change-Id: Ib24db15f3d8c66a9bc1060ba951f3f930a346096","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/xiaohanhuang/tensorflow/commits/a70d68b3acb7c248572a9ce2e90a67392e6c689c"},{"sha":"3ca937c9ef47f662bc613b1086476b0b6f2042d8","author":{"name":"Christian Sigg","email":"bf0bb771be8a27677291ada19f594af5450440c6@google.com"},"message":"Add support for copybara inline directives in BUILD and .bzl files.

Open-source BUILD files are mapped to the Google-internal variants and vice-versa using a [copybara](https://github.com/google/copybara) workflow. This change adds a step to this workflow that allows inline directives to (un-)comment code:

```python
cc_binary(
    ...
    srcs = [
        "common_src.cc",
        # copybara:uncomment(<reason here>) "google_only_src.cc",
        "oss_only_src.cc",  # copybara:comment(<reason here>)
    ],
    deps = [
        ":common_dep",
        # copybara:uncomment_begin(<reason here>)
        # ":google_only_dep",
        # copybara:uncomment_end_and_comment_begin
        ":oss_only_dep",
        # copybara:comment_end
    ],
)
```

The intended use case is to encode relatively small one-off
differences between internal and OSS BUILD files. Making those differences
explicit and inline will hopefully help contributors to write PRs that don't trip up our internal build, and Googlers to write changes that don't break the OSS build.

[{"sha":"42e04b46d19648968537a404f15cebc42b6fab54","author":{"name":"Andrew Clark","email":"46f1a0bd5592a2f9244ca321b129902a06b53e03@andrewclark.io"},"message":"Fix: Detach deleted fiber's alternate, too (#20587)

We need to call `detachFiberAfterEffects` on the fiber's alternate to
clean it up. We're currently not, because the `alternate` field is
cleared during `detachFiberMutation`. So I deferred detaching the
`alternate` until the passive phase. Only the `return` pointer needs to
be detached for semantic purposes.

I don't think there's any good way to test this without using
reflection. It's not even observable using out our "supported"
reflection APIs (`findDOMNode`), or at least not that I can think of.
Which is a good thing, in a way.

It's not really a memory leak, either, because the only reference to the
alternate fiber is from the parent's alternate. Which will be
disconnected the next time the parent is updated or deleted.

It's really only observable if you mess around with internals in ways
you're not supposed to — I found it because a product test in www that
uses Enzyme was doing just that.

In lieu of a new unit test, I confirmed this patch fixes the broken
product test.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/JochLAin/react/commits/42e04b46d19648968537a404f15cebc42b6fab54"},{"sha":"98313aaa7ea58d49eb30ecffc0f9eb6fc1ef467a","author":{"name":"Andrew Clark","email":"46f1a0bd5592a2f9244ca321b129902a06b53e03@andrewclark.io"},"message":"Migrate prepare-release-from-ci to new workflow (#20581)

* Migrate prepare-release-from-ci to new workflow

I added a `--releaseChannel (-r)` argument to script. You must choose
either "stable" or "experimental", because every build job now includes
both channels.

The prepare-release-from-npm script is unchanged since those releases
are downloaded from npm, nt CI.

(As a side note, I think we should start preparing semver releases using

Change-Id: I423db3385e0b80709fc442d8c2991211186e4bcc","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/Manas1820/tensorflow/commits/e687cab61615a95b8aea79120c9f168d4cc30955"},{"sha":"3d28cdc6032ef271510e85df9ab5f95a98f1c6a8","author":{"name":"Andrew Audibert","email":"23f2b5dd93c922fa4b806faa35ad0644038a966e@google.com"},"message":"[tf.data service] Improve cancellation for tf.data service requests.

1. If a DataServiceDataset iterator is cancelled, it will now call TryCancel on its outstanding RPCs.
2. As a result, we can reduce the frequency of returning from blocked round-robin requests to check whether the iterator is cancelled. This may avoid delays in GetNext() that could happen if one consumer reads from a round earlier than others, and needs to perform multiple retries with exponential backoff.
3. Because of (2), server shutdown may take up to 1 minute if a round-robin request is blocked waiting for other consumers. To prevent slow unit tests, certain tests store their servers globally so that they are destroyed immediately at process exit without waiting for their outstanding RPCs to finish.

Running data_service_ops_test.py locally, this CL reduces the time from 27 seconds to 20 seconds

PiperOrigin-RevId: 351837613
Change-Id: Ib24db15f3d8c66a9bc1060ba951f3f930a346096","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/Manas1820/tensorflow/commits/a70d68b3acb7c248572a9ce2e90a67392e6c689c"},{"sha":"3ca937c9ef47f662bc613b1086476b0b6f2042d8","author":{"name":"Christian Sigg","email":"bf0bb771be8a27677291ada19f594af5450440c6@google.com"},"message":"Add support for copybara inline directives in BUILD and .bzl files.

Open-source BUILD files are mapped to the Google-internal variants and vice-versa using a [copybara](https://github.com/google/copybara) workflow. This change adds a step to this workflow that allows inline directives to (un-)comment code:

```python
cc_binary(
    ...
    srcs = [
        "common_src.cc",
        # copybara:uncomment(<reason here>) "google_only_src.cc",
        "oss_only_src.cc",  # copybara:comment(<reason here>)
    ],
    deps = [
        ":common_dep",
        # copybara:uncomment_begin(<reason here>)
        # ":google_only_dep",
        # copybara:uncomment_end_and_comment_begin
        ":oss_only_dep",
        # copybara:comment_end
    ],
)
```

The intended use case is to encode relatively small one-off
differences between internal and OSS BUILD files. Making those differences
explicit and inline will hopefully help contributors to write PRs that don't trip up our internal build, and Googlers to write changes that don't break the OSS build.

[{"sha":"42e04b46d19648968537a404f15cebc42b6fab54","author":{"name":"Andrew Clark","email":"46f1a0bd5592a2f9244ca321b129902a06b53e03@andrewclark.io"},"message":"Fix: Detach deleted fiber's alternate, too (#20587)

We need to call `detachFiberAfterEffects` on the fiber's alternate to
clean it up. We're currently not, because the `alternate` field is
cleared during `detachFiberMutation`. So I deferred detaching the
`alternate` until the passive phase. Only the `return` pointer needs to
be detached for semantic purposes.

I don't think there's any good way to test this without using
reflection. It's not even observable using out our "supported"
reflection APIs (`findDOMNode`), or at least not that I can think of.
Which is a good thing, in a way.

It's not really a memory leak, either, because the only reference to the
alternate fiber is from the parent's alternate. Which will be
disconnected the next time the parent is updated or deleted.

It's really only observable if you mess around with internals in ways
you're not supposed to — I found it because a product test in www that
uses Enzyme was doing just that.

In lieu of a new unit test, I confirmed this patch fixes the broken
product test.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/kalecio/react/commits/42e04b46d19648968537a404f15cebc42b6fab54"},{"sha":"98313aaa7ea58d49eb30ecffc0f9eb6fc1ef467a","author":{"name":"Andrew Clark","email":"46f1a0bd5592a2f9244ca321b129902a06b53e03@andrewclark.io"},"message":"Migrate prepare-release-from-ci to new workflow (#20581)

PiperOrigin-RevId: 351710753
Change-Id: Id906c5a19e299a6236c28e8bc368b19d5e34a56e","distinct":false,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/advaitjain/tensorflow/commits/a4c1164634eb754b5192586b9c24c4e95cda8b7c"},{"sha":"b38e885409c02ee6a43604c3a9f37fc98e925315","author":{"name":"Revan Sopher","email":"fd8618e46eba31404d9f9c653310103aea3024f0@google.com"},"message":"Preserve TPUDistributedVariables passed to TPUStrategy.run().

Normally run() converts all inputs to Tensor, which uses the current value of a variable.
Disabling the cast doesn't work, as a lower MLIR op will cast the variable to Tensor anyway.
Instead we partially apply any TPUDistributedVariables to the function before replicating the remaining inputs.

This doesn't enable any new functionality per se, as it was always possible to implicitly capture the variables in the Python function, but this matches behavior to MirroredStrategy and avoids a simple usability issue.

Note that this change of behavior might break anyone who was relying on the automatic cast happening, in which case the user-side fix would be to manually cast.

Unique TensorFlower","email":"746aced590a184ef4169166e753f7c211e32e5fc@tensorflow.org"},"message":"Control dependency flowing between devices should have a higher priority virtual channel than data flows, otherwise there is a risk of control transfer getting stuck behind a large data transfer. Current channel device implementation is simple, it doesn't model such prioritization.

Instead of adding complexity to channel device, tf-sim could let control deps bypass channel device and (magically) flow across devices in zero time. Control deps are small, latency dominated transfers. Channel devices are only good at modeling BW bound transfers, so bypassing channel device for control deps should not be so bad.
